          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>How to Make Budget Dates Feel Special</h2>
            
            <h3>1. Choose Ambiance Over Price</h3>
            <p>
              A cozy neighborhood spot with candlelight and good music can feel more romantic than an expensive restaurant with harsh lighting and loud crowds. Focus on atmosphere.
            </p>

            <h3>2. Go During Happy Hour</h3>
            <p>
              Many upscale restaurants offer happy hour menus (usually 4-7 PM) with significantly reduced prices. You get the same quality food and ambiance at half the cost.
            </p>

            <h3>3. Share Everything</h3>
            <p>
              Ordering several appetizers or small plates to share is not only more affordable but also more interactive and fun. Plus, you get to try more dishes.
            </p>

            <h3>4. BYOB Restaurants</h3>
            <p>
              Some restaurants allow you to bring your own wine (check first!). This can save $30-$50 on the bill while still feeling special.
            </p>

            <h3>5. Skip the Alcohol</h3>
            <p>
              Drinks can double your bill. Consider restaurants with great mocktails or interesting non-alcoholic options. You'll save money and have clearer heads for conversation.
            </p>

            <h3>6. Lunch Instead of Dinner</h3>
            <p>
              Many restaurants offer lunch versions of their dinner menus at 30-40% lower prices. Weekend lunch dates can be just as romantic.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>Budget Date Night Ideas Beyond Dinner</h2>
            
            <h3>Dinner + Free Activity</h3>
            <p>
              Pair an affordable dinner with free LA activities:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Beach sunset:</strong> Dinner in Venice + walk on the beach</li>
              <li><strong>Griffith Observatory:</strong> Dinner in Los Feliz + free observatory visit</li>
              <li><strong>Arts District:</strong> Dinner + gallery walk (most galleries are free)</li>
              <li><strong>Santa Monica Pier:</strong> Dinner + pier walk and street performers</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Split the Experience</h3>
            <p>
              Instead of a full dinner, try:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Appetizers + Dessert:</strong> Order several small plates and share a dessert</li>
              <li><strong>Coffee + Pastries:</strong> Afternoon coffee dates at bakeries like Republique</li>
              <li><strong>Tacos + Drinks:</strong> Casual Mexican spots with great margaritas</li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>Neighborhood Guide for Budget Dates</h2>
            
            <h3>Silver Lake & Echo Park</h3>
            <p>
              Hip, creative neighborhoods with excellent affordable options. Sqirl, Cliff's Edge, and Botanica offer great food and atmosphere without the West Side prices.
            </p>

            <h3>Venice & Mar Vista</h3>
            <p>
              Beach vibes with reasonable prices. Gjelina's sister restaurants and local spots offer quality dining with a laid-back feel.
            </p>

            <h3>Koreatown</h3>
            <p>
              Incredible value for money. Korean BBQ spots offer interactive dining experiences where you cook together‚Äîfun and affordable.
            </p>

            <h3>Arts District</h3>
            <p>
              Trendy industrial-chic restaurants with reasonable prices. Guerrilla Tacos and Manuela offer Instagram-worthy settings without luxury prices.
            </p>

            <h3>Fairfax District</h3>
            <p>
              Central location with diverse options. Jon & Vinny's and other neighborhood spots offer quality food in casual settings.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>Money-Saving Date Night Strategies</h2>
            
            <h3>The $100 Total Date Night Plan</h3>
            <p>
              Here's how to plan a complete date night for two people under $100:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Dinner:</strong> $60-70 (appetizers, entrees, shared dessert)</li>
              <li><strong>Drinks:</strong> $20-30 (cocktails or wine)</li>
              <li><strong>Parking/Uber:</strong> $10-20</li>
              <li><strong>Total:</strong> $90-120 for a complete evening</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>The $50 Per Person Sweet Spot</h3>
            <p>
              At $50 per person, you can enjoy:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Appetizer or salad to share</li>
              <li>Individual entrees</li>
              <li>Shared dessert</li>
              <li>One drink each (cocktail, wine, or beer)</li>
              <li>Tax and 20% tip included</li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>When to Splurge vs Save</h2>
            
            <h3>Save Money On:</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Regular date nights:</strong> Weekly or bi-weekly dates should be affordable</li>
              <li><strong>Early relationship:</strong> First few dates don't need to be expensive</li>
              <li><strong>Casual occasions:</strong> "Just because" dates can be simple</li>
              <li><strong>Trying new places:</strong> Test affordable spots before committing to pricey ones</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Consider Splurging On:</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Anniversaries:</strong> Milestone celebrations deserve something special</li>
              <li><strong>Birthdays:</strong> Once a year, go all out</li>
              <li><strong>Special achievements:</strong> Promotions, graduations, big wins</li>
              <li><strong>Make-up dates:</strong> After a fight, sometimes a nice gesture helps</li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>Budget Date Night Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
            
            <h3>‚ùå Going TOO Cheap</h3>
            <p>
              Fast food or chain restaurants suggest you didn't put thought into the date. There's a difference between budget-friendly and low-effort.
            </p>

            <h3>‚ùå Skipping Reservations</h3>
            <p>
              Even affordable restaurants can have waits. Make a reservation to show you planned ahead and value your date's time.
            </p>

            <h3>‚ùå Over-Explaining the Budget</h3>
            <p>
              Don't apologize for choosing an affordable spot. Confidence in your choice matters more than the price point.
            </p>

            <h3>‚ùå Ordering the Cheapest Thing</h3>
            <p>
              Order what you actually want. The difference between a $15 and $18 entree won't make or break your budget, but ordering something you don't enjoy will affect the date.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>Free Date Night Add-Ons in LA</h2>
            <p>
              Enhance your budget date with these free activities:
            </p>

            <ul>
              <li><strong>Beach walks:</strong> Sunset stroll after dinner in Santa Monica or Venice</li>
              <li><strong>Griffith Observatory:</strong> Free admission with incredible views</li>
              <li><strong>Getty Center:</strong> Free admission (parking is $20 but worth it)</li>
              <li><strong>Arts District galleries:</strong> Most are free to browse</li>
              <li><strong>Grand Park:</strong> Free events and beautiful downtown views</li>
              <li><strong>Hiking:</strong> Runyon Canyon or Temescal Canyon for active couples</li>
              <li><strong>Street art tours:</strong> Self-guided walks through Venice or Arts District</li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>The Psychology of Budget Dating</h2>
            <p>
              Here's a secret: many people actually prefer budget-friendly dates, especially early in a relationship. Here's why:
            </p>

            <h3>Less Pressure</h3>
            <p>
              When someone spends $300 on dinner, there's an unspoken expectation. Budget dates keep things light and fun without pressure.
            </p>

            <h3>More Authentic</h3>
            <p>
              Casual settings encourage people to be themselves rather than putting on airs. You see the real person, not their "fancy restaurant" persona.
            </p>

            <h3>Better Conversation</h3>
            <p>
              Without the formality of fine dining, conversations flow more naturally. You're not worried about using the right fork or impressing the sommelier.
            </p>

            <h3>Sustainable Dating</h3>
            <p>
              If every date costs $200+, you can't go out often. Affordable dates mean more time together, which builds stronger relationships.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="content-section">
